post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_26162679_26162809_0": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6685}}, "n3337": {"so_26162679_26162809_0": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 6440}}, "n4659": {"so_26162679_26162809_0": {"length": 4, "quality": 1.0, "section_id": 8160}}}, "26162809": {"Id": "26162809", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>An inner class is a friend of the class it is declared within.</p>\n<p>It would have no meaning to do it with a <code>friend</code> specifier since it would be an inner class with private-access to the outer one.</p>\n<p>And, formally, the standard says:</p>\n<p><em>[class.friend]/p2</em></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_26162679_26162809_0\">A class shall not be defined in a friend declaration</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "1938163", "LastActivityDate": "2014-10-02T14:20:43.793", "Score": "3", "CreationDate": "2014-10-02T14:15:28.167", "ParentId": "26162679", "CommentCount": "1", "OwnerUserId": "1938163", "LastEditDate": "2014-10-02T14:20:43.793"}, "26162679": {"ViewCount": "58", "Body": "<p>Why friend functions can be defined</p>\n<pre><code>class CL\n{\n    friend void fnc(){}\n};\n</code></pre>\n<p>but friend classes can't?</p>\n<pre><code>class CL\n{\n    friend class FriendClass{}; //error\n};\n</code></pre>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "26162809", "Title": "Definition of friend functions and classes", "CreationDate": "2014-10-02T14:09:18.703", "Id": "26162679", "CommentCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2014-10-02T14:22:09.403", "Score": "1", "OwnerUserId": "3514538", "Tags": "<c++><class><friend>", "AnswerCount": "1"}});